==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|geostran dæg|lang=ang}}, equivalent to {{prefix|yester|day}}; compounded from
* Old English {{term|geostran|lang=ang||yesterday}}, from {{proto|Germanic|gestra-}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|dʰǵʰyes-}};
* Old English {{term|dæg|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|dagaz}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|dʰegʰ-|to burn}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈjɛstədeɪ/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈjɛstɚdeɪ/}}
* {{audio|en-us-yesterday.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|En-uk-yesterday.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|eɪ}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The [[day]] before [[today]]. 'Today is the child of yesterday and the parent of tomorrow'. It can also understand as a day ago.
#: '''''Yesterday''' was rainy, but by this morning it had begun to snow.''
# The (recent) [[past]], often [[disparaging]].
#: '''''Yesterday's''' technology.''
#: ''All our '''yesterdays''' have lighted fools the way to dusty death.'' [Shakespeare, ''Macbeth'', Act 5, Scene 5]

====Usage notes====
* The term yesterdays is unusual and often poetic for the recent past, e.g. "all our yesterdays have come back to haunt us."

